const SEC_OBS = {
  id:"obs",title:"Observability & Monitoring",icon:"📊",ib:"rgba(163,117,255,.12)",ic:"#a378ff",
  grp:"infra",bar:"#a378ff",tglow:"rgba(163,117,255,.07)",
  desc:"Metrics, logs, traces, Prometheus, Grafana, distributed tracing, SLI/SLO/SLA, APM tools, and production debugging.",
  tags:["Prometheus","Grafana","Tracing","OpenTelemetry","SLO","Metrics","Logs"],
  qs:[
    {q:"What are the three pillars of observability and how do they differ?",d:"easy", id:1,
     a:"The three pillars of observability are <strong>metrics</strong>, <strong>logs</strong>, and <strong>traces</strong>. Together they provide visibility into system behavior and health.<br><br><strong>1. Metrics (quantitative data):</strong><ul><li>Time-series numerical data aggregated over time</li><li>Examples: request rate, error rate, CPU usage, memory usage, latency percentiles (p50, p95, p99)</li><li>Cheap to store and query at scale</li><li>Answer: \"What is happening?\" and \"How much/how fast?\"</li><li>Tools: Prometheus, Grafana, Datadog, CloudWatch</li></ul><br><strong>2. Logs (event data):</strong><ul><li>Discrete events with timestamps and contextual information</li><li>Examples: application logs, access logs, error messages, stack traces</li><li>Expensive to store at scale (structured JSON logs help)</li><li>Answer: \"What exactly happened?\" and \"Why did it fail?\"</li><li>Tools: ELK Stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana), Splunk, Loki, CloudWatch Logs</li></ul><br><strong>3. Traces (request flow data):</strong><ul><li>Track a single request as it flows through distributed services</li><li>Examples: HTTP request spans across microservices, database queries, external API calls</li><li>Each trace has a unique trace ID with multiple spans</li><li>Answer: \"Where is the bottleneck?\" and \"Which service is slow?\"</li><li>Tools: Jaeger, Zipkin, Tempo, X-Ray, Datadog APM</li></ul><br><br><strong>How they work together:</strong><ol><li><strong>Metrics</strong> alert you: \"API error rate spiked at 3 PM\"</li><li><strong>Logs</strong> show you: \"NullPointerException in UserService line 42\"</li><li><strong>Traces</strong> reveal: \"The bottleneck is a slow database query in OrderService taking 2 seconds\"</li></ol><br><strong>Correlation:</strong> Use <code>trace_id</code> in logs to link metrics → traces → logs for root cause analysis."},

    {q:"What are RED metrics and Golden Signals? How do they differ?",d:"medium", id:2,
     a:"<strong>RED metrics</strong> and <strong>Golden Signals</strong> are frameworks for monitoring service health, focusing on user-facing behavior.<br><br><strong>RED Metrics (for services):</strong><br>Coined by Tom Wilkie (Grafana Labs). Focus on <em>request-driven</em> services (APIs, microservices).<br><ol><li><strong>R</strong> — Rate: requests per second</li><li><strong>E</strong> — Errors: percentage of failed requests</li><li><strong>D</strong> — Duration: latency distribution (p50, p95, p99)</li></ol><br><strong>Example Prometheus queries:</strong><br><pre>rate(http_requests_total[5m])                    # Rate\nrate(http_requests_total{status=~\"5..\"}[5m])    # Errors\nhistogram_quantile(0.95, http_request_duration_seconds)  # p95 latency</pre><br><strong>Golden Signals (Google SRE):</strong><br>From Google's SRE book. Broader framework covering both services and infrastructure.<br><ol><li><strong>Latency:</strong> time to serve a request (distinguish success vs error latency)</li><li><strong>Traffic:</strong> demand on the system (requests/sec, transactions/sec)</li><li><strong>Errors:</strong> rate of failed requests (5xx, 4xx, exceptions)</li><li><strong>Saturation:</strong> how \"full\" the system is (CPU, memory, disk, thread pool usage)</li></ol><br><strong>Key difference:</strong><ul><li>RED = user-facing service metrics only</li><li>Golden Signals = service + infrastructure resource utilization</li></ul><br><strong>Which to use?</strong><ul><li><strong>RED:</strong> microservices dashboards, API monitoring</li><li><strong>Golden Signals:</strong> comprehensive monitoring including infrastructure (databases, queues, caches)</li></ul><br><strong>Spring Boot + Micrometer example:</strong><br><pre>@RestController\npublic class UserController {\n  private final MeterRegistry meterRegistry;\n\n  @GetMapping(\"/users/{id}\")\n  @Timed(value = \"users.get\", percentiles = {0.5, 0.95, 0.99})\n  public User getUser(@PathVariable String id) {\n    return userService.findById(id);\n  }\n}</pre>Micrometer automatically tracks rate, errors, and duration."},

    {q:"How do you instrument a Spring Boot application with Micrometer for Prometheus?",d:"medium", id:3,
     a:"<strong>Micrometer</strong> is the metrics facade for Spring Boot (like SLF4J for logging). It integrates with Prometheus, Datadog, New Relic, and others.<br><br><strong>1. Add dependencies:</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-starter-actuator&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;\n&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;io.micrometer&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;micrometer-registry-prometheus&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;</pre><br><strong>2. Enable Prometheus endpoint:</strong><br><pre># application.properties\nmanagement.endpoints.web.exposure.include=health,info,prometheus\nmanagement.metrics.export.prometheus.enabled=true\nmanagement.endpoint.prometheus.enabled=true</pre><br><strong>3. Access metrics:</strong><br><pre>curl http://localhost:8080/actuator/prometheus</pre>Returns metrics in Prometheus format:<br><pre>http_server_requests_seconds_count{method=\"GET\",status=\"200\",uri=\"/users\"} 142\nhttp_server_requests_seconds_sum{method=\"GET\",status=\"200\",uri=\"/users\"} 2.5\njvm_memory_used_bytes{area=\"heap\"} 524288000</pre><br><strong>4. Custom metrics — Counter:</strong><br><pre>@Service\npublic class OrderService {\n  private final Counter orderCounter;\n\n  public OrderService(MeterRegistry registry) {\n    this.orderCounter = Counter.builder(\"orders.created\")\n      .description(\"Total orders created\")\n      .tag(\"type\", \"online\")\n      .register(registry);\n  }\n\n  public void createOrder(Order order) {\n    // ... business logic\n    orderCounter.increment();\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>5. Custom metrics — Gauge:</strong><br><pre>@Component\npublic class QueueMetrics {\n  @Autowired\n  public QueueMetrics(MeterRegistry registry, OrderQueue queue) {\n    Gauge.builder(\"queue.size\", queue, Queue::size)\n      .description(\"Current queue size\")\n      .register(registry);\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>6. Custom metrics — Timer:</strong><br><pre>@Service\npublic class PaymentService {\n  private final Timer paymentTimer;\n\n  public PaymentService(MeterRegistry registry) {\n    this.paymentTimer = Timer.builder(\"payments.process.time\")\n      .description(\"Payment processing time\")\n      .publishPercentiles(0.5, 0.95, 0.99)\n      .register(registry);\n  }\n\n  public void processPayment(Payment payment) {\n    paymentTimer.record(() -> {\n      // payment processing logic\n    });\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>7. Prometheus scrape config:</strong><br><pre>scrape_configs:\n  - job_name: 'spring-boot'\n    metrics_path: '/actuator/prometheus'\n    static_configs:\n    - targets: ['localhost:8080']</pre><br><strong>8. Common Spring Boot metrics (auto-configured):</strong><ul><li><code>http_server_requests_seconds</code> — request duration</li><li><code>jvm_memory_used_bytes</code> — heap/non-heap memory</li><li><code>jvm_gc_pause_seconds</code> — GC pause time</li><li><code>tomcat_threads_current</code> — active threads</li><li><code>hikaricp_connections_active</code> — database connections</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is distributed tracing and how does it work with trace IDs and span IDs?",d:"medium", id:4,
     a:"<strong>Distributed tracing</strong> tracks a single request as it propagates through multiple microservices, creating a tree of <strong>spans</strong> grouped by a unique <strong>trace ID</strong>.<br><br><strong>Key concepts:</strong><br><br><strong>Trace:</strong> represents the entire request journey (e.g., user clicks \"checkout\")<br><strong>Span:</strong> a single unit of work (e.g., HTTP call to payment service, database query)<br><strong>Trace ID:</strong> unique identifier for the entire trace (e.g., <code>abc123</code>)<br><strong>Span ID:</strong> unique identifier for each span within a trace (e.g., <code>span-1</code>, <code>span-2</code>)<br><strong>Parent Span ID:</strong> links child spans to their parent<br><br><strong>Example trace tree:</strong><br><pre>Trace ID: abc123\n├─ Span 1 (span-1): API Gateway [200ms]\n   ├─ Span 2 (span-2): Order Service [150ms]\n   │  ├─ Span 3 (span-3): Database Query [50ms]\n   │  └─ Span 4 (span-4): Inventory Service [80ms]\n   └─ Span 5 (span-5): Payment Service [30ms]</pre><br><strong>How propagation works (W3C Trace Context):</strong><ol><li>API Gateway generates a <code>traceparent</code> header: <code>00-abc123-span1-01</code></li><li>Header includes: trace ID, span ID, trace flags</li><li>Each service extracts the trace ID and creates a new span</li><li>Services pass the header downstream with updated span IDs</li></ol><br><strong>Example HTTP headers:</strong><br><pre>traceparent: 00-abc123-span2-01\ntracestate: vendor=value</pre><br><strong>Spring Boot + Micrometer Tracing (OpenTelemetry):</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;io.micrometer&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;micrometer-tracing-bridge-otel&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;\n&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;io.opentelemetry&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;opentelemetry-exporter-zipkin&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;</pre><br><strong>Configuration:</strong><br><pre>management.tracing.sampling.probability=0.1  # sample 10% of requests\nmanagement.zipkin.tracing.endpoint=http://zipkin:9411/api/v2/spans</pre><br><strong>Automatic instrumentation:</strong><ul><li>Spring MVC / WebFlux (HTTP requests)</li><li>RestTemplate / WebClient (outbound HTTP)</li><li>JDBC / R2DBC (database queries)</li><li>Kafka / RabbitMQ (messaging)</li></ul><br><strong>Adding to logs (MDC):</strong><br><pre>@Slf4j\n@RestController\npublic class OrderController {\n  @GetMapping(\"/orders/{id}\")\n  public Order getOrder(@PathVariable String id) {\n    log.info(\"Fetching order {}\", id);  // automatically includes trace_id\n    return orderService.findById(id);\n  }\n}</pre>Logback pattern:<br><pre>&lt;pattern&gt;%d{ISO8601} [%X{traceId}/%X{spanId}] %-5level %logger{36} - %msg%n&lt;/pattern&gt;</pre><br><strong>Benefits:</strong><ul><li>Identify slow services in a multi-service call chain</li><li>Debug production issues without reproducing locally</li><li>Correlate logs across services using trace ID</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is OpenTelemetry and how does it unify observability?",d:"medium", id:5,
     a:"<strong>OpenTelemetry</strong> (OTel) is a vendor-neutral observability framework that provides a single standard for collecting <strong>metrics</strong>, <strong>logs</strong>, and <strong>traces</strong> from applications.<br><br><strong>Why OpenTelemetry?</strong><br>Before OTel, each vendor had proprietary SDKs:<ul><li>Jaeger for tracing</li><li>Prometheus for metrics</li><li>Separate log shippers (Fluentd, Logstash)</li></ul>Result: instrumentation lock-in, vendor switching is hard.<br><br><strong>OpenTelemetry solves this:</strong><ul><li>One SDK for metrics, logs, traces</li><li>Vendor-agnostic: export to Prometheus, Jaeger, Datadog, New Relic, etc.</li><li>Auto-instrumentation for popular frameworks (Spring Boot, Express, Django)</li></ul><br><strong>Architecture:</strong><br><pre>Application (OTel SDK) → OTel Collector → Backends (Prometheus, Jaeger, etc.)</pre><br><strong>Key components:</strong><br><br><strong>1. OTel SDK:</strong> instrumentation libraries for Java, Go, Python, etc.<br><br><strong>2. OTel Collector:</strong> receives telemetry, processes it, and exports to multiple backends<br><pre>receivers:  # receive telemetry\n  otlp:\n    protocols:\n      grpc:\n      http:\nprocessors:  # transform data\n  batch:\n  memory_limiter:\nexporters:  # send to backends\n  prometheus:\n    endpoint: \"prometheus:9090\"\n  jaeger:\n    endpoint: \"jaeger:14250\"</pre><br><strong>3. OTel Protocol (OTLP):</strong> wire format for sending telemetry (gRPC or HTTP)<br><br><strong>Spring Boot integration:</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;io.micrometer&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;micrometer-tracing-bridge-otel&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;\n&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;io.opentelemetry&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;opentelemetry-exporter-otlp&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;</pre><br><strong>Configuration:</strong><br><pre>management.tracing.enabled=true\nmanagement.otlp.tracing.endpoint=http://otel-collector:4318/v1/traces</pre><br><strong>Semantic conventions:</strong> standardized attribute names<br><pre>http.method = \"GET\"\nhttp.url = \"https://api.example.com/users\"\nhttp.status_code = 200\nservice.name = \"order-service\"\nservice.version = \"1.2.0\"</pre><br><strong>Trace propagation (W3C Trace Context):</strong><br><pre>traceparent: 00-trace_id-span_id-01</pre>Automatically injected into HTTP headers, Kafka headers, etc.<br><br><strong>Benefits:</strong><ul><li>Avoid vendor lock-in (switch from Jaeger to Tempo without code changes)</li><li>Unified telemetry pipeline (metrics + traces + logs)</li><li>Rich ecosystem of exporters (30+ backends supported)</li><li>Auto-instrumentation (no code changes for common frameworks)</li></ul><br><strong>Adoption:</strong> Datadog, New Relic, Dynatrace, AWS X-Ray, Google Cloud Trace all support OTel natively."},

    {q:"What are SLIs, SLOs, and SLAs? How do they relate to error budgets?",d:"medium", id:6,
     a:"<strong>SLI</strong>, <strong>SLO</strong>, and <strong>SLA</strong> are frameworks from Google SRE for defining and measuring reliability.<br><br><strong>SLI (Service Level Indicator):</strong><ul><li>A <em>quantitative measure</em> of service performance</li><li>Examples: availability %, latency (p95), error rate %, throughput</li><li>Must be measurable from the user's perspective</li></ul><br><strong>Example SLIs:</strong><br><pre>Availability SLI = (successful requests / total requests) × 100\nLatency SLI = % of requests served in < 200ms\nError SLI = (non-5xx responses / total responses) × 100</pre><br><strong>SLO (Service Level Objective):</strong><ul><li>A <em>target value</em> for an SLI over a time window</li><li>Example: \"99.9% of requests succeed (4xx/5xx < 0.1%) over 30 days\"</li><li>Example: \"95% of requests complete in < 200ms over 7 days\"</li><li>Internal goal — used to prioritize work and measure reliability</li></ul><br><strong>Example SLOs:</strong><br><pre>SLO 1: Availability ≥ 99.9% (monthly)\nSLO 2: p95 latency ≤ 200ms (weekly)\nSLO 3: Error rate ≤ 0.1% (daily)</pre><br><strong>SLA (Service Level Agreement):</strong><ul><li>A <em>contract</em> with customers defining consequences if SLO is missed</li><li>Example: \"We guarantee 99.95% uptime. If we miss it, you get a 10% refund.\"</li><li>Externally facing, legally binding</li><li>SLA should be less strict than internal SLO (buffer for safety)</li></ul><br><strong>Relationship:</strong><br><pre>SLA (99.95%) &lt; SLO (99.99%) ≤ SLI (actual: 99.991%)</pre><br><strong>Error Budget:</strong><ul><li>The <em>allowed downtime</em> before violating an SLO</li><li>Formula: <code>Error Budget = 100% - SLO</code></li><li>Used to balance reliability vs velocity</li></ul><br><strong>Example:</strong><br><pre>SLO: 99.9% availability over 30 days\nError Budget: 0.1% = 43 minutes of downtime per month</pre><br>If you have 43 minutes of budget remaining → safe to take risks (deploy, experiment)<br>If budget is exhausted → freeze deployments, focus on reliability<br><br><strong>Using error budgets for decision-making:</strong><br><pre>IF error_budget &gt; 50%:\n  → Accelerate feature development\nELSE IF error_budget &lt; 10%:\n  → Freeze non-critical deploys\n  → Focus on reliability improvements\n  → Postmortem recent incidents</pre><br><strong>Prometheus alerting for SLO:</strong><br><pre>- alert: SLOViolation\n  expr: |\n    (sum(rate(http_requests_total{status!~\"5..\"}[30d]))\n     / sum(rate(http_requests_total[30d]))) &lt; 0.999\n  annotations:\n    summary: \"SLO violated: availability &lt; 99.9%\"</pre><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Define 3-5 SLIs per service (availability, latency, error rate)</li><li>SLOs should be achievable but challenging (not 100%)</li><li>Review SLOs quarterly — adjust based on user expectations</li><li>Burn rate alerts: alert if error budget will be exhausted before window ends</li></ul>"},

    {q:"How do you set up alerting in Prometheus and Grafana?",d:"medium", id:7,
     a:"<strong>Prometheus</strong> evaluates alert rules and sends notifications to <strong>Alertmanager</strong>. <strong>Grafana</strong> can also alert on dashboards.<br><br><strong>Prometheus Alerting Flow:</strong><br><pre>Prometheus → Alertmanager → Notification Channels (Slack, PagerDuty, Email)</pre><br><strong>1. Define alert rules in Prometheus:</strong><br><pre># /etc/prometheus/alert_rules.yml\ngroups:\n- name: backend_alerts\n  interval: 30s\n  rules:\n  - alert: HighErrorRate\n    expr: |\n      rate(http_requests_total{status=~\"5..\"}[5m]) &gt; 0.05\n    for: 5m\n    labels:\n      severity: critical\n      team: backend\n    annotations:\n      summary: \"High 5xx error rate on {{ $labels.instance }}\"\n      description: \"Error rate is {{ $value | humanizePercentage }} over the last 5 minutes.\"\n\n  - alert: HighLatency\n    expr: |\n      histogram_quantile(0.95,\n        rate(http_request_duration_seconds_bucket[5m])) &gt; 0.5\n    for: 10m\n    labels:\n      severity: warning\n    annotations:\n      summary: \"High p95 latency on {{ $labels.instance }}\"\n\n  - alert: ServiceDown\n    expr: up{job=\"spring-boot\"} == 0\n    for: 1m\n    labels:\n      severity: critical\n    annotations:\n      summary: \"Service {{ $labels.instance }} is down\"</pre><br><strong>2. Load rules in Prometheus config:</strong><br><pre># prometheus.yml\nrule_files:\n  - \"alert_rules.yml\"\n\nalertmanager:\n  static_configs:\n  - targets:\n    - \"alertmanager:9093\"</pre><br><strong>3. Configure Alertmanager:</strong><br><pre># alertmanager.yml\nglobal:\n  slack_api_url: 'https://hooks.slack.com/services/YOUR/WEBHOOK'\n\nroute:\n  group_by: ['alertname', 'severity']\n  group_wait: 10s\n  group_interval: 10s\n  repeat_interval: 12h\n  receiver: 'slack-critical'\n  routes:\n  - match:\n      severity: warning\n    receiver: 'slack-warning'\n\nreceivers:\n- name: 'slack-critical'\n  slack_configs:\n  - channel: '#alerts-critical'\n    title: '{{ .GroupLabels.alertname }}'\n    text: '{{ range .Alerts }}{{ .Annotations.summary }}\\n{{ end }}'\n\n- name: 'slack-warning'\n  slack_configs:\n  - channel: '#alerts-warning'</pre><br><strong>4. Grafana alerting (alternative):</strong><br>Create alert rules directly in Grafana dashboards:<ol><li>Edit panel → Alert tab</li><li>Define query: <code>rate(http_requests_total{status=~\"5..\"}[5m])</code></li><li>Set condition: <code>WHEN avg() IS ABOVE 0.05</code></li><li>Configure notification channel (Slack, PagerDuty)</li></ol><br><strong>Grafana contact points:</strong><br><pre># Slack notification\ncontact_points:\n  - name: slack-alerts\n    type: slack\n    settings:\n      url: https://hooks.slack.com/services/YOUR/WEBHOOK\n      text: '{{ template \"slack.default.text\" . }}'</pre><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li><strong>For duration:</strong> add <code>for: 5m</code> to avoid flapping alerts</li><li><strong>Severity levels:</strong> <code>critical</code> (page on-call), <code>warning</code> (ticket), <code>info</code> (log)</li><li><strong>Alert on symptoms, not causes:</strong> alert on \"high latency\" not \"high CPU\"</li><li><strong>Actionable alerts:</strong> include runbook links in annotations</li><li><strong>Grouping:</strong> group alerts by service to avoid alert storms</li></ul><br><strong>Example — SLO-based alert:</strong><br><pre>- alert: ErrorBudgetExhausted\n  expr: |\n    (1 - (sum(rate(http_requests_total{status!~\"5..\"}[7d]))\n          / sum(rate(http_requests_total[7d])))) &gt; 0.001\n  annotations:\n    summary: \"Error budget exhausted (SLO: 99.9%)\"</pre>"},

    {q:"What is structured logging and why is it important for observability?",d:"easy", id:8,
     a:"<strong>Structured logging</strong> means logging in a machine-readable format (typically JSON) instead of plain text, making logs easier to search, filter, and correlate.<br><br><strong>Unstructured (plain text) log:</strong><br><pre>2024-04-08 14:32:15 INFO User john@example.com logged in from 192.168.1.5</pre><br><strong>Structured (JSON) log:</strong><br><pre>{\n  \"timestamp\": \"2024-04-08T14:32:15Z\",\n  \"level\": \"INFO\",\n  \"message\": \"User logged in\",\n  \"user_email\": \"john@example.com\",\n  \"ip_address\": \"192.168.1.5\",\n  \"trace_id\": \"abc123\",\n  \"service\": \"auth-service\"\n}</pre><br><strong>Why structured logging?</strong><ol><li><strong>Searchable fields:</strong> query by <code>user_email</code>, <code>ip_address</code>, <code>trace_id</code> without regex parsing</li><li><strong>Correlation:</strong> link logs across services using <code>trace_id</code></li><li><strong>Aggregation:</strong> count errors by <code>service</code> or <code>error_code</code></li><li><strong>Machine-readable:</strong> ingest into Elasticsearch, Loki, Datadog without custom parsers</li><li><strong>Context-rich:</strong> include metadata (user ID, request ID, environment)</li></ol><br><strong>Spring Boot + Logback JSON logging:</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;net.logstash.logback&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;logstash-logback-encoder&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n  &lt;version&gt;7.4&lt;/version&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;</pre><br><strong>logback-spring.xml:</strong><br><pre>&lt;appender name=\"JSON\" class=\"ch.qos.logback.core.ConsoleAppender\"&gt;\n  &lt;encoder class=\"net.logstash.logback.encoder.LogstashEncoder\"&gt;\n    &lt;customFields&gt;{\"service\":\"order-service\"}&lt;/customFields&gt;\n  &lt;/encoder&gt;\n&lt;/appender&gt;</pre><br><strong>Adding context with MDC (Mapped Diagnostic Context):</strong><br><pre>@Slf4j\n@RestController\npublic class OrderController {\n  @GetMapping(\"/orders/{id}\")\n  public Order getOrder(@PathVariable String id) {\n    MDC.put(\"user_id\", SecurityContextHolder.getContext().getAuthentication().getName());\n    MDC.put(\"order_id\", id);\n    log.info(\"Fetching order\");\n    MDC.clear();\n    return orderService.findById(id);\n  }\n}</pre>Output:<br><pre>{\n  \"message\": \"Fetching order\",\n  \"user_id\": \"user123\",\n  \"order_id\": \"ord456\",\n  \"trace_id\": \"abc123\"\n}</pre><br><strong>Automatic trace ID injection (Spring Boot 3+):</strong><br>With Micrometer Tracing, <code>trace_id</code> and <code>span_id</code> are auto-added to MDC.<br><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Always include <code>timestamp</code>, <code>level</code>, <code>service</code>, <code>trace_id</code></li><li>Use consistent field names across services (<code>user_id</code>, not <code>userId</code>)</li><li>Don't log PII (passwords, credit cards, SSNs) — use <code>[REDACTED]</code></li><li>Log at appropriate levels: ERROR (needs attention), WARN (potential issue), INFO (business events), DEBUG (developer info)</li></ul>"},

    {q:"How do you correlate metrics, logs, and traces for debugging?",d:"hard", id:9,
     a:"Correlating <strong>metrics</strong>, <strong>logs</strong>, and <strong>traces</strong> enables fast root cause analysis by linking high-level trends to detailed request-level data.<br><br><strong>Correlation strategy:</strong><br><pre>Metrics → Traces → Logs</pre><ol><li><strong>Metrics</strong> alert: \"Error rate spiked at 14:32\"</li><li>Query <strong>traces</strong> from that time: find slow/failing requests</li><li>Use <code>trace_id</code> to search <strong>logs</strong>: see exact error messages and stack traces</li></ol><br><strong>The glue: trace_id</strong><br>A unique identifier propagated across services and embedded in metrics, logs, and traces.<br><br><strong>Example debugging workflow:</strong><br><br><strong>Step 1 — Metric alert fires:</strong><br><pre>Alert: HighErrorRate\nQuery: rate(http_requests_total{status=\"500\"}[5m]) &gt; 0.05\nTime: 2024-04-08 14:32:00</pre><br><strong>Step 2 — Check Grafana dashboard:</strong><br>Filter metrics by time range → see error spike on <code>/api/orders</code> endpoint<br><br><strong>Step 3 — Query traces in Jaeger/Tempo:</strong><br><pre>service=order-service\nstatus=error\ntime=14:30-14:35</pre>Find a failing trace with <code>trace_id=abc123</code>. Visualize spans:<br><pre>Trace abc123 [500ms, ERROR]\n├─ API Gateway [10ms]\n├─ Order Service [480ms]\n│  ├─ Database Query [400ms, ERROR] ← bottleneck\n│  └─ Inventory Service [50ms]</pre><br><strong>Step 4 — Search logs by trace_id:</strong><br>Elasticsearch/Loki query:<br><pre>trace_id:\"abc123\"</pre>Logs:<br><pre>{\n  \"trace_id\": \"abc123\",\n  \"level\": \"ERROR\",\n  \"message\": \"Database query timeout\",\n  \"error\": \"PSQLException: connection timeout after 5000ms\",\n  \"query\": \"SELECT * FROM orders WHERE status='pending'\"\n}</pre><br><strong>Step 5 — Root cause identified:</strong><br>Database query timed out → check database metrics → slow disk I/O<br><br><strong>Implementation — Spring Boot:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Enable tracing (Micrometer Tracing):</strong><br><pre>management.tracing.enabled=true\nmanagement.tracing.sampling.probability=0.1  # sample 10%</pre><br><strong>2. Auto-inject trace_id into logs:</strong><br><pre>&lt;pattern&gt;%d{ISO8601} [%X{traceId}/%X{spanId}] %level %logger - %msg%n&lt;/pattern&gt;</pre><br><strong>3. Add trace_id to metrics (exemplars):</strong><br><pre>http_requests_total{status=\"500\",trace_id=\"abc123\"} 1</pre>Grafana shows trace link next to metric data point.<br><br><strong>4. Propagate trace_id across services:</strong><br>Spring Boot automatically propagates via HTTP headers:<br><pre>traceparent: 00-abc123-span2-01</pre><br><strong>Unified observability platforms:</strong><ul><li><strong>Grafana Stack:</strong> Loki (logs) + Tempo (traces) + Prometheus (metrics) — linked by trace_id</li><li><strong>Datadog:</strong> APM, logs, metrics all correlated by trace_id</li><li><strong>Elastic Observability:</strong> Elasticsearch (logs), APM (traces), Metricbeat (metrics)</li></ul><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Always propagate trace_id (use OpenTelemetry or W3C Trace Context)</li><li>Include trace_id in all logs (use MDC)</li><li>Configure trace sampling intelligently (100% in dev, 1-10% in prod)</li><li>Use exemplars in Prometheus to link metrics → traces</li></ul>"},

    {q:"What is the difference between push-based and pull-based monitoring?",d:"medium", id:10,
     a:"<strong>Push-based</strong> and <strong>pull-based</strong> are two approaches for collecting metrics from applications.<br><br><strong>Pull-based (Prometheus model):</strong><ul><li>Monitoring system <em>scrapes</em> metrics from application endpoints</li><li>Application exposes <code>/metrics</code> HTTP endpoint</li><li>Prometheus pulls metrics every <code>scrape_interval</code> (e.g., 15s)</li></ul><br><strong>Example Prometheus scrape config:</strong><br><pre>scrape_configs:\n  - job_name: 'spring-boot'\n    scrape_interval: 15s\n    static_configs:\n    - targets: ['app1:8080', 'app2:8080']</pre><br><strong>Pros:</strong><ul><li>Centralized control (Prometheus decides when to scrape)</li><li>Service discovery (auto-detect new instances via Kubernetes, Consul)</li><li>Simple application setup (just expose an endpoint)</li><li>Built-in health checks (Prometheus marks targets as down if scrape fails)</li></ul><br><strong>Cons:</strong><ul><li>Requires network access from Prometheus to all targets (firewall issues)</li><li>Difficult for short-lived jobs (batch jobs, Lambda) — they exit before scrape</li><li>Scrape interval limits time resolution (can't capture sub-15s spikes)</li></ul><br><strong>Push-based (Datadog, CloudWatch, StatsD model):</strong><ul><li>Application <em>sends</em> metrics to the monitoring system</li><li>Metrics are pushed via UDP (StatsD), HTTP, or agent</li></ul><br><strong>Example Micrometer + Datadog:</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;io.micrometer&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;micrometer-registry-datadog&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;\n\nmanagement.metrics.export.datadog.api-key=${DATADOG_API_KEY}\nmanagement.metrics.export.datadog.step=10s  # push every 10s</pre><br><strong>Pros:</strong><ul><li>Works for short-lived jobs (push before exit)</li><li>No firewall issues (outbound connections only)</li><li>Real-time (metrics sent immediately, not waiting for scrape)</li><li>Works behind NAT / private networks</li></ul><br><strong>Cons:</strong><ul><li>Application must know monitoring system address (tight coupling)</li><li>Harder to detect application failures (no heartbeat/scrape failure)</li><li>Network overhead (constant outbound traffic)</li><li>Metric loss if monitoring system is down</li></ul><br><strong>Hybrid approach — Pushgateway:</strong><br>For batch jobs in a pull-based system (Prometheus):<ol><li>Job pushes metrics to Pushgateway</li><li>Prometheus scrapes Pushgateway</li></ol><br><strong>Example:</strong><br><pre>curl -X POST http://pushgateway:9091/metrics/job/batch_job/instance/worker1 \\\n  --data 'batch_records_processed 1234'</pre><br><strong>When to use pull:</strong> long-lived services, microservices in Kubernetes<br><strong>When to use push:</strong> serverless (Lambda), batch jobs, edge devices<br><br><strong>Modern trend:</strong> OpenTelemetry supports both (OTLP push + Prometheus pull)."},

    {q:"What is log aggregation and how do ELK and Loki differ?",d:"medium", id:11,
     a:"<strong>Log aggregation</strong> collects logs from multiple services into a centralized system for searching, filtering, and analysis.<br><br><strong>Why log aggregation?</strong><ul><li>Microservices generate logs across 100+ containers</li><li>SSH-ing to individual instances doesn't scale</li><li>Correlation: search logs from multiple services by <code>trace_id</code></li></ul><br><br><strong>ELK Stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana):</strong><br><pre>Application → Logstash/Filebeat → Elasticsearch → Kibana (UI)</pre><br><strong>Components:</strong><ol><li><strong>Elasticsearch:</strong> distributed search engine, stores logs as JSON documents with full-text indexing</li><li><strong>Logstash/Filebeat:</strong> log shippers that collect, parse, and send logs to Elasticsearch</li><li><strong>Kibana:</strong> web UI for querying logs, visualizations, dashboards</li></ol><br><strong>How it works:</strong><br><pre># Filebeat config\nfilebeat.inputs:\n- type: log\n  paths:\n    - /var/log/app/*.log\n  json.keys_under_root: true\n\noutput.elasticsearch:\n  hosts: [\"elasticsearch:9200\"]\n  index: \"app-logs-%{+yyyy.MM.dd}\"</pre><br><strong>Pros:</strong><ul><li>Powerful full-text search</li><li>Rich querying (filters, aggregations, regex)</li><li>Battle-tested, mature ecosystem</li></ul><br><strong>Cons:</strong><ul><li>Expensive (high memory/CPU, scales poorly with log volume)</li><li>Complex to operate (cluster management, shard balancing)</li><li>Indexing overhead (every field is indexed)</li></ul><br><br><strong>Grafana Loki (\"like Prometheus, but for logs\"):</strong><br><pre>Application → Promtail/Fluentd → Loki → Grafana (UI)</pre><br><strong>Key difference:</strong> Loki only indexes <em>labels</em> (metadata), not log content.<br><pre># Labels indexed: {service=\"order-service\", level=\"error\"}\n# Log content NOT indexed (stored as compressed chunks)</pre><br><strong>How it works:</strong><br><pre># Promtail config\nserver:\n  http_listen_port: 9080\n\npositions:\n  filename: /tmp/positions.yaml\n\nclients:\n  - url: http://loki:3100/loki/api/v1/push\n\nscrape_configs:\n- job_name: system\n  static_configs:\n  - targets:\n      - localhost\n    labels:\n      job: app-logs\n      __path__: /var/log/app/*.log</pre><br><strong>Query example (LogQL):</strong><br><pre>{service=\"order-service\", level=\"error\"} |= \"NullPointerException\"</pre><ul><li><code>{service=\"order-service\"}</code> — label filter (indexed)</li><li><code>|= \"NullPointerException\"</code> — grep-like search (not indexed)</li></ul><br><strong>Pros:</strong><ul><li>Cost-effective (10x cheaper than Elasticsearch at scale)</li><li>Easy to operate (simple, horizontally scalable)</li><li>Seamless Grafana integration (metrics + logs in one view)</li><li>Label-based queries familiar to Prometheus users</li></ul><br><strong>Cons:</strong><ul><li>No full-text indexing (slower regex searches)</li><li>Less rich querying than Elasticsearch</li><li>Relatively new (less mature than ELK)</li></ul><br><br><strong>When to use ELK:</strong> deep log analysis, compliance (audit logs), complex aggregations<br><strong>When to use Loki:</strong> cost-sensitive, already using Grafana, Prometheus-style workflows<br><br><strong>Modern trend:</strong> Loki gaining adoption due to cost + simplicity, but ELK still dominant in enterprises."},

    {q:"How do you implement health checks in Spring Boot for Kubernetes?",d:"easy", id:12,
     a:"<strong>Health checks</strong> tell Kubernetes whether a container is alive and ready to serve traffic. Spring Boot Actuator provides health endpoints out of the box.<br><br><strong>Two types of health checks:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Liveness probe:</strong> is the app running? (if no → restart container)<br><strong>2. Readiness probe:</strong> is the app ready to serve traffic? (if no → remove from load balancer)<br><br><strong>Setup:</strong><br><br><strong>Step 1 — Add Actuator dependency:</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;org.springframework.boot&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;spring-boot-starter-actuator&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;</pre><br><strong>Step 2 — Enable health endpoints:</strong><br><pre># application.properties\nmanagement.endpoints.web.exposure.include=health,info\nmanagement.endpoint.health.probes.enabled=true\nmanagement.endpoint.health.show-details=always</pre><br><strong>Spring Boot 2.3+ provides separate endpoints:</strong><ul><li><code>/actuator/health/liveness</code></li><li><code>/actuator/health/readiness</code></li></ul><br><strong>Step 3 — Configure Kubernetes probes:</strong><br><pre>apiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nspec:\n  template:\n    spec:\n      containers:\n      - name: myapp\n        image: myapp:1.0\n        ports:\n        - containerPort: 8080\n        livenessProbe:\n          httpGet:\n            path: /actuator/health/liveness\n            port: 8080\n          initialDelaySeconds: 30\n          periodSeconds: 10\n          failureThreshold: 3\n        readinessProbe:\n          httpGet:\n            path: /actuator/health/readiness\n            port: 8080\n          initialDelaySeconds: 10\n          periodSeconds: 5\n          failureThreshold: 3</pre><br><strong>What health checks include (by default):</strong><ul><li><strong>Liveness:</strong> basic app state (always returns UP unless app crashes)</li><li><strong>Readiness:</strong> database connectivity, downstream service availability, disk space</li></ul><br><strong>Custom health indicator:</strong><br><pre>@Component\npublic class DatabaseHealthIndicator implements HealthIndicator {\n  @Autowired\n  private DataSource dataSource;\n\n  @Override\n  public Health health() {\n    try (Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection()) {\n      if (conn.isValid(1)) {\n        return Health.up()\n          .withDetail(\"database\", \"PostgreSQL\")\n          .withDetail(\"version\", conn.getMetaData().getDatabaseProductVersion())\n          .build();\n      }\n    } catch (Exception e) {\n      return Health.down(e).build();\n    }\n    return Health.down().build();\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Readiness vs Liveness guidelines:</strong><br><br><strong>Liveness:</strong> lightweight, doesn't check dependencies<ul><li>Don't check database (causes cascading restarts)</li><li>Check: app thread pool not deadlocked, out-of-memory</li></ul><br><strong>Readiness:</strong> check all dependencies<ul><li>Check: database reachable, Redis reachable, downstream services</li><li>If dependencies fail → readiness fails → Pod removed from Service (but not restarted)</li></ul><br><strong>Testing:</strong><br><pre>curl http://localhost:8080/actuator/health/liveness\n# {\"status\":\"UP\"}\n\ncurl http://localhost:8080/actuator/health/readiness\n# {\"status\":\"UP\",\"components\":{\"db\":{\"status\":\"UP\"},\"redis\":{\"status\":\"UP\"}}}</pre>"},

    {q:"What is an APM tool and how does it differ from metrics/logs/traces?",d:"medium", id:13,
     a:"<strong>APM (Application Performance Monitoring)</strong> tools combine metrics, logs, and traces into a unified platform with automatic instrumentation, profiling, and root cause analysis.<br><br><strong>Popular APM tools:</strong> Datadog, New Relic, Dynatrace, AppDynamics, Elastic APM<br><br><strong>What APM provides beyond basic observability:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Auto-instrumentation:</strong><ul><li>Install agent → automatic tracing without code changes</li><li>Instruments: HTTP, database, cache, external APIs, messaging</li></ul><br><strong>2. End-to-end transaction tracing:</strong><ul><li>See entire request flow across 10+ microservices</li><li>Flame graphs showing time spent in each method</li></ul><br><strong>3. Code-level profiling:</strong><ul><li>CPU/memory profiling at the method level</li><li>Identify slow database queries, N+1 queries, memory leaks</li></ul><br><strong>4. Service maps:</strong><ul><li>Visualize service dependencies</li><li>Automatically detect topology changes</li></ul><br><strong>5. Error tracking:</strong><ul><li>Group errors by stack trace fingerprint</li><li>Show which deployment introduced an error</li><li>Link errors to traces and logs</li></ul><br><strong>6. Real User Monitoring (RUM):</strong><ul><li>Frontend performance metrics (page load, JavaScript errors)</li><li>Correlated with backend traces</li></ul><br><br><strong>Example — Datadog APM setup:</strong><br><pre># Docker\ndocker run -d \\\n  -e DD_API_KEY=${DD_API_KEY} \\\n  -e DD_APM_ENABLED=true \\\n  -e DD_APM_NON_LOCAL_TRAFFIC=true \\\n  -p 8126:8126 \\\n  datadog/agent:latest\n\n# Java app with agent\njava -javaagent:/path/to/dd-java-agent.jar \\\n  -Ddd.service=order-service \\\n  -Ddd.env=production \\\n  -Ddd.version=1.2.0 \\\n  -jar app.jar</pre><br><strong>Example — Elastic APM setup:</strong><br><pre>&lt;dependency&gt;\n  &lt;groupId&gt;co.elastic.apm&lt;/groupId&gt;\n  &lt;artifactId&gt;elastic-apm-agent&lt;/artifactId&gt;\n  &lt;version&gt;1.36.0&lt;/version&gt;\n&lt;/dependency&gt;\n\njava -javaagent:elastic-apm-agent.jar \\\n  -Delastic.apm.service_name=order-service \\\n  -Delastic.apm.server_urls=http://apm-server:8200 \\\n  -jar app.jar</pre><br><strong>APM vs DIY Observability:</strong><br><br><strong>DIY (Prometheus + Loki + Jaeger):</strong><ul><li>✅ Open source, no vendor lock-in</li><li>✅ Cost-effective at scale</li><li>❌ Manual instrumentation</li><li>❌ Separate UIs for metrics/logs/traces</li><li>❌ No profiling, error grouping, service maps</li></ul><br><strong>APM (Datadog, New Relic):</strong><ul><li>✅ Auto-instrumentation (install agent)</li><li>✅ Unified UI (metrics, logs, traces, profiling)</li><li>✅ Powerful analytics, ML-based anomaly detection</li><li>❌ Expensive ($100-500/host/month)</li><li>❌ Vendor lock-in</li></ul><br><strong>When to use APM:</strong><ul><li>Need quick time-to-value (no instrumentation work)</li><li>Want comprehensive features (profiling, RUM, service maps)</li><li>Have budget</li></ul><br><strong>When to use DIY:</strong><ul><li>Cost-sensitive (millions in APM bills at scale)</li><li>Want control and customization</li><li>Already invested in Grafana/Prometheus ecosystem</li></ul><br><strong>Hybrid approach:</strong> Use Grafana Cloud (managed Prometheus + Loki + Tempo) or Elastic Cloud (managed ELK + APM) for simplicity without extreme cost."},

    {q:"What is sampling in distributed tracing and why is it necessary?",d:"medium", id:14,
     a:"<strong>Sampling</strong> means capturing only a subset of traces (e.g., 1% or 10%) instead of tracing every request, to reduce storage and overhead.<br><br><strong>Why sampling is necessary:</strong><ul><li>Tracing 100% of requests at scale generates massive data (TB/day)</li><li>Storage costs are prohibitive (Jaeger, Tempo, Datadog charge per span)</li><li>Performance overhead: adding trace context to every request impacts latency</li></ul><br><strong>Example volume calculation:</strong><br><pre>100,000 req/sec × 10 spans/trace × 1 KB/span = 1 GB/sec = 86 TB/day (unsampled)</pre>With 1% sampling → 860 GB/day (manageable)<br><br><strong>Sampling strategies:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Probabilistic sampling (most common):</strong><ul><li>Randomly sample X% of traces</li><li>Example: 10% → 1 in 10 traces captured</li></ul><br><strong>Spring Boot config:</strong><br><pre>management.tracing.sampling.probability=0.1  # 10%</pre><br><strong>2. Rate limiting:</strong><ul><li>Sample at most N traces/second</li><li>Example: 100 traces/sec</li></ul><br><strong>3. Tail-based sampling (smart sampling):</strong><ul><li>Capture all traces initially (in memory)</li><li>Decide after the trace completes whether to keep it</li><li>Keep: slow traces, error traces, specific users</li><li>Discard: fast, successful traces</li></ul><br><strong>Advantages:</strong><ul><li>Capture 100% of errors without 100% overhead</li><li>Capture long-latency requests automatically</li></ul><br><strong>Disadvantages:</strong><ul><li>Complex (requires stateful collector)</li><li>Higher memory usage</li></ul><br><strong>4. Adaptive sampling:</strong><ul><li>Adjust sampling rate based on traffic volume</li><li>High traffic → lower sampling; low traffic → higher sampling</li></ul><br><strong>Example — Jaeger tail-based sampling:</strong><br><pre>policies:\n  - name: error-traces\n    type: status_code\n    status_code:\n      status_codes: [ERROR]\n  - name: slow-traces\n    type: latency\n    latency:\n      threshold_ms: 1000\n  - name: probabilistic-policy\n    type: probabilistic\n    probabilistic:\n      sampling_percentage: 1</pre>This keeps:<ul><li>100% of errors</li><li>100% of traces &gt; 1s</li><li>1% of everything else</li></ul><br><strong>Head-based vs tail-based:</strong><br><br><strong>Head-based (sampling decision at start):</strong><ul><li>Pros: simple, low memory, works with stateless architecture</li><li>Cons: can't sample based on outcome (errors, latency)</li></ul><br><strong>Tail-based (sampling decision at end):</strong><ul><li>Pros: intelligent sampling (keep interesting traces)</li><li>Cons: requires buffering, stateful collector</li></ul><br><strong>Best practices:</strong><ul><li>Start with 10% probabilistic sampling</li><li>Production: 1-5% for high-traffic services</li><li>Always sample 100% of errors (via tail-based or custom logic)</li><li>Use <code>SAMPLED</code> flag in trace headers to propagate sampling decision</li></ul><br><strong>OpenTelemetry sampling:</strong><br><pre>sampler:\n  type: parentbased_traceidratio\n  argument: 0.1  # 10%</pre>This respects upstream sampling decisions (if parent span is sampled, sample children too)."},

    {q:"How do you debug production issues without reproducing locally?",d:"hard", id:15,
     a:"Production debugging requires leveraging observability tools to understand system behavior in real-time without local reproduction.<br><br><strong>Step-by-step production debugging workflow:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Start with alerts/symptoms:</strong><ul><li>\"Error rate spiked at 14:32\"</li><li>\"Latency increased from 100ms to 500ms\"</li><li>\"Customer reported failed checkout\"</li></ul><br><strong>2. Check metrics (high-level view):</strong><br>Grafana/Datadog dashboard:<ul><li>HTTP request rate, error rate (RED metrics)</li><li>CPU, memory, thread pool usage (Golden Signals)</li><li>Database connection pool, query latency</li><li>External API call success rate</li></ul>Identify: which service, which endpoint, what time?<br><br><strong>3. Drill into traces (request-level view):</strong><br>Jaeger/Tempo query:<br><pre>service=order-service\nhttp.status_code=500\ntimestamp=2024-04-08 14:30-14:35</pre>Find a failing trace → visualize spans:<br><pre>Trace abc123 [2.5s, ERROR]\n├─ API Gateway [10ms]\n├─ Order Service [2.4s]\n│  ├─ Database Query [50ms]\n│  ├─ Payment Service [2.3s, TIMEOUT] ← bottleneck\n│  └─ Inventory Check [20ms]</pre>Identified: Payment Service timeout after 2.3s<br><br><strong>4. Search logs by trace_id:</strong><br>Elasticsearch/Loki:<br><pre>trace_id:\"abc123\"</pre>Logs from Order Service:<br><pre>{\n  \"trace_id\": \"abc123\",\n  \"level\": \"ERROR\",\n  \"message\": \"Payment service timeout\",\n  \"error\": \"SocketTimeoutException: Read timed out after 2000ms\",\n  \"payment_gateway\": \"stripe\",\n  \"amount\": 99.99\n}</pre><br><strong>5. Check external dependencies:</strong><ul><li>Is Stripe API down? (check status page)</li><li>Network latency to Stripe increased?</li><li>Rate limiting?</li></ul><br><strong>6. Query error aggregations:</strong><br>Datadog/Sentry: group errors by stack trace fingerprint<br><pre>SocketTimeoutException: Read timed out\n  at PaymentGateway.charge(PaymentGateway.java:42)\n  at OrderService.createOrder(OrderService.java:87)\n\n500 occurrences in last 5 minutes</pre><br><strong>7. Correlate with deployment:</strong><ul><li>Was there a recent deploy? (<code>kubectl rollout history</code>)</li><li>Feature flag change?</li><li>Configuration change?</li></ul><br><strong>8. Check database slow queries:</strong><br>PostgreSQL:<br><pre>SELECT query, mean_exec_time, calls\nFROM pg_stat_statements\nWHERE mean_exec_time &gt; 1000\nORDER BY mean_exec_time DESC\nLIMIT 10;</pre><br><strong>9. Profiling (if available):</strong><br>Datadog Continuous Profiler → CPU flame graph → identify hot code paths<br><br><strong>10. Reproduce hypothesis (optional):</strong><br>Based on findings, try to reproduce locally:<ul><li>Increase timeout to 10s → works</li><li>Hypothesis: Stripe API degraded → confirmed</li></ul><br><br><strong>Tools by debugging stage:</strong><br><table><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Tool</th></tr><tr><td>High-level trend</td><td>Grafana, Datadog dashboards</td></tr><tr><td>Request-level detail</td><td>Jaeger, Tempo, X-Ray traces</td></tr><tr><td>Exact error messages</td><td>Elasticsearch, Loki logs</td></tr><tr><td>Code-level profiling</td><td>Datadog Profiler, JFR, async-profiler</td></tr><tr><td>Database performance</td><td>pg_stat_statements, EXPLAIN ANALYZE</td></tr><tr><td>Correlation</td><td>trace_id linking metrics → traces → logs</td></tr></table><br><strong>Key principles:</strong><ul><li><strong>Top-down:</strong> start broad (metrics), narrow down (traces), drill into detail (logs)</li><li><strong>Correlation:</strong> link data using trace_id, timestamps, metadata</li><li><strong>Hypothesis-driven:</strong> form theories, test with queries, validate</li><li><strong>Document:</strong> create runbooks for common issues</li></ul><br><strong>What you can't do without observability:</strong><ul><li>Reproduce rare concurrency bugs</li><li>Debug issues caused by specific production data</li><li>Identify cascading failures across services</li><li>Diagnose intermittent external API issues</li></ul><br><strong>Summary:</strong> Production debugging = metrics (what?) + traces (where?) + logs (why?)"},

    {q:"What is alert fatigue and how do you prevent it?",d:"medium", id:16,
     a:"<strong>Alert fatigue</strong> occurs when teams receive too many alerts, causing them to ignore or miss critical issues. It's a major problem in on-call culture.<br><br><strong>Symptoms of alert fatigue:</strong><ul><li>Alerts ignored or muted</li><li>On-call engineers miss pages</li><li>False positives normalize deviance (\"it's probably nothing\")</li><li>Burnout and decreased responsiveness</li></ul><br><strong>Root causes:</strong><ol><li><strong>Too many alerts:</strong> alerting on everything \"just in case\"</li><li><strong>Noisy alerts:</strong> flapping (on → off → on)</li><li><strong>False positives:</strong> alerts fire but no real issue</li><li><strong>Non-actionable alerts:</strong> \"High CPU\" without context or remediation</li></ol><br><br><strong>Prevention strategies:</strong><br><br><strong>1. Alert on symptoms, not causes:</strong><br>❌ Bad: <code>CPU &gt; 80%</code> (might be normal under load)<br>✅ Good: <code>p95 latency &gt; 500ms for 5 minutes</code> (user-facing impact)<br><br>❌ Bad: <code>Disk &gt; 90%</code><br>✅ Good: <code>Disk will fill in &lt; 24 hours at current rate</code><br><br><strong>2. Use SLO-based alerting:</strong><br>Alert when error budget is at risk, not on individual errors:<br><pre>- alert: ErrorBudgetBurn\n  expr: |\n    (1 - (sum(rate(http_requests{status!~\"5..\"}[1h]))\n          / sum(rate(http_requests[1h])))) &gt; 0.01\n  for: 5m\n  annotations:\n    summary: \"Error budget burning too fast (1% in 1 hour)\"</pre><br><strong>3. Add hysteresis (for duration):</strong><br>Don't alert on transient spikes:<br><pre>expr: error_rate &gt; 0.05\nfor: 10m  # Must be high for 10 consecutive minutes</pre><br><strong>4. Severity levels:</strong><ul><li><strong>Critical:</strong> page on-call (user-facing outage, SLO breach)</li><li><strong>Warning:</strong> create ticket (potential issue, manual investigation)</li><li><strong>Info:</strong> log only (FYI, no action needed)</li></ul><br><strong>5. Actionable alerts:</strong><br>Every alert should have:<ul><li><strong>What:</strong> clear description of the problem</li><li><strong>Why:</strong> impact (users can't checkout, revenue loss)</li><li><strong>How:</strong> runbook link with remediation steps</li></ul><br><pre>annotations:\n  summary: \"Payment service error rate &gt; 5%\"\n  description: \"Users cannot complete checkout. Revenue impacted.\"\n  runbook: \"https://wiki.example.com/runbooks/payment-errors\"</pre><br><strong>6. Alert consolidation (grouping):</strong><br>Group related alerts to avoid alert storms:<br><pre># Alertmanager grouping\nroute:\n  group_by: ['alertname', 'cluster', 'service']\n  group_wait: 30s\n  group_interval: 5m\n  repeat_interval: 4h</pre><br><strong>7. Flap detection:</strong><br>Suppress alerts that rapidly toggle on/off:<br><pre>- alert: HighLatency\n  expr: p95_latency &gt; 500\n  for: 10m  # Must stay high for 10min (prevents flapping)</pre><br><strong>8. Scheduled maintenance windows:</strong><br>Silence alerts during planned maintenance:<br><pre># Alertmanager silence\namtool silence add \\\n  alertname=DatabaseDown \\\n  --duration=2h \\\n  --comment=\"Planned database upgrade\"</pre><br><strong>9. Alert tuning process:</strong><ul><li>Review alerts weekly</li><li>Track false positive rate (target &lt; 5%)</li><li>Remove alerts with &gt; 50% false positives</li><li>Adjust thresholds based on historical data</li></ul><br><strong>10. On-call rotation best practices:</strong><ul><li>Limit to 5-10 pages/week per person</li><li>Compensate on-call engineers (time off, extra pay)</li><li>Postmortems for every page (was it valid?)</li></ul><br><strong>Metrics to track:</strong><ul><li>Alerts per week</li><li>False positive rate</li><li>Mean time to acknowledge (MTTA)</li><li>Mean time to resolve (MTTR)</li><li>Alerts muted/snoozed</li></ul><br><strong>Golden rule:</strong> If an alert doesn't require immediate human action, it shouldn't page anyone."},

    {q:"What is the difference between white-box and black-box monitoring?",d:"easy", id:17,
     a:"<strong>White-box monitoring</strong> and <strong>black-box monitoring</strong> represent two perspectives on system observability.<br><br><strong>White-box monitoring (internal perspective):</strong><ul><li>Monitors system internals: metrics, logs, traces</li><li>Requires instrumentation (application exports metrics)</li><li>Examples: JVM heap usage, HTTP request rate, database query latency, thread pool size</li><li>Provides detailed insights into <em>how</em> the system works</li><li>Proactive: can detect issues before they affect users</li></ul><br><strong>Tools:</strong> Prometheus, Datadog, Micrometer, application logs<br><br><strong>Example white-box metrics:</strong><br><pre>jvm_memory_used_bytes{area=\"heap\"}\nhttp_server_requests_seconds_count\ndatabase_connection_pool_active\nkafka_consumer_lag</pre><br><br><strong>Black-box monitoring (external perspective):</strong><ul><li>Monitors system behavior from the outside (user's view)</li><li>No access to internals — treats system as a \"black box\"</li><li>Examples: uptime checks, synthetic transactions, HTTP health checks</li><li>Validates that the system <em>actually works</em> end-to-end</li><li>Reactive: detects issues users are experiencing</li></ul><br><strong>Tools:</strong> Pingdom, UptimeRobot, Blackbox Exporter (Prometheus), synthetic monitoring (Datadog Synthetics)<br><br><strong>Example black-box checks:</strong><br><pre># HTTP health check\nGET https://api.example.com/health\nExpect: 200 OK in &lt; 500ms\n\n# Synthetic transaction\n1. Login as test user\n2. Add item to cart\n3. Complete checkout\nExpect: Order ID returned in &lt; 3s</pre><br><br><strong>When to use white-box:</strong><ul><li>Debugging (need detailed insights)</li><li>Performance optimization (identify bottlenecks)</li><li>Capacity planning (predict resource needs)</li><li>Early warning (detect issues before user impact)</li></ul><br><strong>When to use black-box:</strong><ul><li>Uptime monitoring (is the site up?)</li><li>Multi-region health checks</li><li>Validate critical user flows (login, checkout)</li><li>Detect network/DNS issues</li><li>Ensure SLA compliance</li></ul><br><br><strong>Complementary approach:</strong><br>Use both:<ul><li><strong>White-box:</strong> alerts on internal symptoms (error rate &gt; 5%)</li><li><strong>Black-box:</strong> validates external availability (health check fails)</li></ul><br><strong>Example combined monitoring:</strong><ol><li><strong>Black-box:</strong> synthetic check fails (can't complete checkout)</li><li><strong>White-box:</strong> drill into traces → Payment Service timing out</li><li><strong>White-box:</strong> database connection pool exhausted</li></ol><br><strong>Analogy:</strong><ul><li><strong>White-box:</strong> car dashboard (RPM, fuel, temperature)</li><li><strong>Black-box:</strong> test drive (does it start? does it drive?)</li></ul><br><strong>Best practice:</strong> Always have black-box checks for critical user journeys, even if you have comprehensive white-box monitoring. Internal metrics can lie (app reports healthy but DNS is broken)."}
  ]
};
